# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: embos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:embos/cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:embos/cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:embos/cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:embos/cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:embos/cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:embos/cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:embos/cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:embos/cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:embos/cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:embos/cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:embos/cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:embos/cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:embos/cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:embos/cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:embos/cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:embos/cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:embos/cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:embos/cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:embos/cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:embos/cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:embos/cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:embos/cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:embos/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:embos/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:embos/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:embos/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:embos/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:embos/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:embos/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:embos/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:embos/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:embos/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:embos/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:embos/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:embos/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:embos/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:embos/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:embos/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:embos/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:embos/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:embos/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:embos/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:embos/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:embos/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:embos/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:embos/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:embos/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:embos/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:embos/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:embos/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:embos/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:embos/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:embos/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:embos/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:embos/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:embos/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:embos/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:embos/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:embos/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:embos/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:embos/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:embos/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:embos/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:embos/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:embos/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:embos/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:embos/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:embos/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:embos/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:embos/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:embos/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:embos/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:embos/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:embos/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:embos/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:embos/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:embos/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:embos/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:embos/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:embos/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:embos/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:embos/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:embos/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:embos/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:embos/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:embos/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:embos/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:embos/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:embos/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:embos/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:embos/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:embos/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:embos/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:embos/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:embos/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:embos/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:embos/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:embos/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:embos/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:embos/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:embos/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:embos/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:embos/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:embos/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:embos/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:embos/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:embos/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:embos/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:embos/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:embos/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] Segger Microcontroller was founded in 1992 by Rolf Segger in Hilden, Germany.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] The first product was the real-time operating system (RTOS), now named embOS.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] It was followed by emWin two years later.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] Initial products focused on RTOS and middleware products.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] However, the company later produced ISP-programming tools (Flasher) and debug probes (J-Link).
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] In 2015, Segger introduced Embedded Studio, their cross-platform IDE for central processing units conforming to the ARM architecture, though recent versions are also used by RISC-V.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] All products are developed, maintained and updated in Germany except for Embedded Studio, which is primarily developed by a team of developers in the United Kingdom.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] It is also repackaged and sold as an OEM item by Analog Devices as the mIDASLink, Atmel as the SAM-ICE, Digi International as the Digi JTAG Link, and IAR Systems as the J-Link and the J-Link KS.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] This is the only JTAG emulator that can add Segger's patented flash breakpoint software to a debugger to enable the setting of multiple breakpoints in flash while running on an ARM device which is typically hindered by the limited availability of hardware breakpoints.
[src:embos/segger-microcontroller-systems] In the following table, the top group are trace devices, the bottom group are educational / hobbyist devices.
[src:embos/stm32] In addition to its microcontroller lines, STMicroelectronics has introduced microprocessor (MPU) offerings such as the MP1 and MP2 series into the STM32 family.
[src:embos/stm32] These processors are based around single or dual ARM Cortex-A cores combined with an ARM Cortex-M core.
[src:embos/stm32] Cortex-A application processors include a memory management unit (MMU), enabling them to run advanced operating systems such as Linux.
[src:embos/stm32] The **STM32** family of the microcontroller ICs is based on various 32-bit RISC ARM Cortex-M cores.
[src:embos/stm32] STMicroelectronics licenses the ARM Processor IP from ARM Holdings and integrates them with custom-designed peripherals to create complete microcontroller solutions.
[src:embos/stm32] Each STM32 microcontroller is designed for specific performance, power efficiency, and feature requirements, making them suitable for a wide range of embedded applications.
[src:embos/stm32] The following tables summarize the STM32 family of microcontrollers (MCUs) and microprocessors (MPUs).
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 is the third ARM family by STMicroelectronics.
[src:embos/stm32] It follows their earlier STR9 family based on the ARM9E core, and STR7 family based on the ARM7TDMI core.
[src:embos/stm32] The following is the history of how the STM32 family has evolved.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 family consists of many series of microcontrollers.
[src:embos/stm32] Each STM32 microcontroller series is based upon a specific ARM Cortex-M processor core.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F0-series are the first group of ARM Cortex-M0 chips in the STM32 family.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F1-series was the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M3 core and considered their mainstream ARM microcontrollers.
[src:embos/stm32] The F1-series has evolved over time by increasing CPU speed, size of internal memory, variety of peripherals.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F2-series of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M3 core.
[src:embos/stm32] It is the most recent and fastest Cortex-M3 series.
[src:embos/stm32] The F2 is pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F4-series.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F3-series is the second group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M4F core.
[src:embos/stm32] The F3 is almost pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F1-series.
[src:embos/stm32] The distinguishing feature for this series is presence of four fast, 12-bit, simultaneous sampling ADCs (multiplexer to over 30 channels), and four matched, 8 MHz bandwidth op-amps with all pins exposed and additionally internal PGA (Programmable Gain Array) network.
[src:embos/stm32] The exposed pads allow for a range of analog signal conditioning circuits like band-pass filters, anti-alias filters, charge amplifiers, integrators/differentiators, 'instrumentation' high-gain differential inputs, and other.
[src:embos/stm32] This eliminates need for external op-amps for many applications.
[src:embos/stm32] The built-in two-channel DAC has arbitrary waveform as well as a hardware-generated waveform (sine, triangle, noise etc.) capability.
[src:embos/stm32] All analog devices can be completely independent, or partially internally connected, meaning that one can have nearly everything that is needed for an advanced measurement and sensor interfacing system in a single chip.
[src:embos/stm32] The four ADCs can be simultaneously sampled making a wide range of precision analog control equipment possible.
[src:embos/stm32] It is also possible to use a hardware scheduler for the multiplexer array, allowing good timing accuracy when sampling more than 4 channels, independent of the main processor thread.
[src:embos/stm32] The sampling and multiplexing trigger can be controlled from a variety of sources including timers and built-in comparators, allowing for irregular sampling intervals where needed.
[src:embos/stm32] STM32F37/38xxx integrate a 14-effective number of bits delta-sigma ADC.
[src:embos/stm32] The op-amps inputs feature 2-to-1 analog multiplexer, allowing for a total of eight analog channels to be pre-processed using the op-amp; all the op-amp outputs can be internally connected to ADCs.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F4-series is the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M4F core.
[src:embos/stm32] The F4-series is also the first STM32 series to have DSP and floating-point instructions.
[src:embos/stm32] The F4 is pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F2-series and adds higher clock speed, 64 KB CCM static RAM, full-duplex I²S, improved real-time clock, and faster ADCs.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 F7-series is a group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M7F core.
[src:embos/stm32] Many of the F7 series are pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F4-series.
[src:embos/stm32] Many of STM32F76xxx and STM32F77xxx models have a digital filter for sigma-delta modulators (DFSDM) interface.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 H7-series is a group of high performance STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M7F core with double-precision floating point unit and optional second Cortex-M4F core with single-precision floating point.
[src:embos/stm32] Cortex-M7F core can reach working frequency up to 600 MHz, while Cortex-M4F - up to 240 MHz.
[src:embos/stm32] Each of these cores can work independently or as master/slave core.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 L0-series is the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M0+ core.
[src:embos/stm32] This series targets low power applications.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 L1-series was the first group of STM32 microcontrollers with a primary goal of ultra-low power usage for battery-powered applications.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 L4-series is an evolution of STM32L1-series of ultra-low power microcontrollers.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM32 L4+-series is expansion of STM32L4-series of ultra-low power microcontrollers, providing more performance, more embedded memory and richer graphics and connectivity features while keeping ultra-low-power capability.
[src:embos/stm32] The following boards have Arduino Nano pin-compatible male pin headers with 0.6-inch row-to-row DIP-30 footprint, but these boards have 3.3 volt logic I/O, instead of 5 volt logic I/O for an Arduino Nano "R3" and Nano R4.
[src:embos/stm32] The following boards have Arduino Uno R3 pin-compatible female pin headers for Arduino shields, but these boards have 3.3 volt logic I/O, instead of 5 volt logic I/O for an Arduino Uno.
[src:embos/stm32] There are three Nucleo board types, each supporting a different STM32 IC package footprint.
[src:embos/stm32] As of fall 2025, there were over eighty Nucleo board variations: 9 of Nucleo-32, 39 of Nucleo-64, 28 of Nucleo-144; 1 obsolete Nucleo-32, 5 obsolete Nucleo-144.
[src:embos/stm32] All Nucleo boards by STMicroelectronics have an additional onboard ST-LINK host adapter chip which supplies SWD debugging, virtual COM port, and mass storage over USB.
[src:embos/stm32] The debugger embedded on Nucleo boards can be converted to the SEGGER J-Link debugger protocol.
[src:embos/stm32] Though some STM32 microcontrollers have a real-time clock (RTC) peripheral and/or battery-back SRAM, none of the Nucleo boards have a battery holder.
[src:embos/stm32] Nucleo-32 boards have 32-pin STM32 ICs and Arduino Nano pin-compatible male pin headers with 0.6-inch row-to-row DIP-30 footprint.
[src:embos/stm32] Nucleo-64 boards have 64-pin STM32 ICs (except Nucleo-C031C6 and Nucleo-C051C8 have 48-pin ICs), Arduino Uno R3 female headers for shields, ST Morpho male pin headers (two 19x2), some board have a second USB connector, one board (NUCLEO-C092RC) has a CAN-FD bus connector.
[src:embos/stm32] Nucleo-144 boards have 144-pin STM32 ICs (except Nucleo-H7S3L8 has 225-pin IC and Nucleo-N657X0-Q has 264-pin IC), Arduino Uno R3 female headers for shields, ST Zio female headers, ST Morpho male pin headers (two 19x2), some have a second USB connector, some have a RJ45 Ethernet connector.
[src:embos/stm32] The unlisted Nucleo-F429ZI, Nucleo-F746ZG, Nucleo-H743ZI, Nucleo-H743ZI2, Nucleo-H745ZI-Q are obsolete.
[src:embos/stm32] The following table compares various features of official Nucleo boards from STMicroelectronics.
[src:embos/stm32] The left half of the table contains details about each board, the right half of the table contains details about the microcontroller (MCU) on each board.
[src:embos/stm32] Table columns can be sorted by clicking on the arrows in the top row.
[src:embos/stm32] Various terms have been shortened or simplified to reduce the column widths: mini means miniUSB, micro means microUSB, conn means connector, dev means device.
[src:embos/stm32] The suffixes MHz and KB have been moved to the top row.
[src:embos/stm32] The Nucleo board types have been reduced to numeric values.
[src:embos/stm32] See "Table notes" (under table) for additional explainations.
[src:embos/stm32] The following **Discovery** evaluation boards are sold by STMicroelectronics to provide a quick and easy way for engineers to evaluate their microcontroller chips.
[src:embos/stm32] These kits are available from various distributors for less than US$20.
[src:embos/stm32] The STMicroelectronics evaluation product licence agreement forbids their use in any production system or any product that is offered for sale.
[src:embos/stm32] Each board includes an on-board ST-LINK for programming and debugging via a Mini-B USB connector.
[src:embos/stm32] The power for each board is provided by a choice of the 5 V via the USB cable, or an external 5 V power supply.
[src:embos/stm32] They can be used as output power supplies of 3 V or 5 V (current must be less than 100 mA).
[src:embos/stm32] All Discovery boards also include a voltage regulator, reset button, user button, multiple LEDs, SWD header on top of each board, and rows of header pins on the bottom.
[src:embos/stm32] An open-source project was created to allow Linux to communicate with the ST-LINK debugger.
[src:embos/stm32] ChibiOS/RT, a free RTOS, has been ported to run on some of the Discovery boards.
[src:embos/stm32] The following evaluation kits are sold by STMicroelectronics.
[src:embos/stm32] A ready-to-use Java development kits for its STM32 microcontrollers.
[src:embos/stm32] The STM3220G-JAVA Starter Kit combines an evaluation version of IS2T's MicroEJ Software Development Kit (SDK) and the STM32F2 series microcontroller evaluation board providing everything engineers need to start their projects.
[src:embos/stm32] MicroEJ provides extended features to create, simulate, test and deploy Java applications in embedded systems.
[src:embos/stm32] Support for Graphical User Interface (GUI) development includes a widget library, design tools including storyboarding, and tools for customizing fonts.
[src:embos/stm32] STM32 microcontrollers that embed Java have a Part Number that ends with J like STM32F205VGT6J.
[src:embos/stm32] All STM32 microcontrollers have a ROM'ed bootloader that supports loading a binary image into its flash memory using one or more peripherals (varies by STM32 family).
[src:embos/stm32] Since all STM32 bootloaders support loading from the USART peripheral and most boards connect the USART to RS-232 or a USB-to-UART adapter IC, thus it's a universal method to program the STM32 microcontroller.
[src:embos/stm32] This method requires the target to have a way to enable/disable booting from the ROM'ed bootloader (i.e. jumper / switch / button).
[src:embos/stm32] The amount of documentation for all ARM chips can be daunting, especially for newcomers.
[src:embos/stm32] As microprocessors have increased in capability and complexity, the documentation has grown.
[src:embos/stm32] The total documentation for all ARM chips consists of documents from the IC manufacturer (STMicroelectronics) and documents from CPU core vendor (ARM Holdings).
[src:embos/stm32] STMicroelectronics has additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:embos/stm32] See External Links section for links to official STM32 and ARM documents.
[src:embos/task-computing] In computing, a **task** is a unit of execution or a unit of work.
[src:embos/task-computing] The term is ambiguous; precise alternative terms include *process*, light-weight process, *thread* (for execution), *step*, *request*, or *query* (for work).
[src:embos/task-computing] In the adjacent diagram, there are queues of incoming work to do and outgoing completed work, and a thread pool of threads to perform this work.
[src:embos/task-computing] Either the work units themselves or the threads that perform the work can be referred to as "tasks", and these can be referred to respectively as requests/responses/threads, incoming tasks/completed tasks/threads (as illustrated), or requests/responses/tasks.
[src:embos/task-computing] In the sense of "unit of execution", in some operating systems, a task is synonymous with a process, and in others with a thread.
[src:embos/task-computing] In non-interactive execution (batch processing), a task is a unit of execution within a job, with the task itself typically a process.
[src:embos/task-computing] The term "multitasking" primarily refers to the processing sense – multiple tasks *executing* at the same time – but has nuances of the work sense of multiple tasks being *performed* at the same time.
[src:embos/task-computing] In online systems, tasks most commonly correspond to a single *request* (in request–response architectures) or a *query* (in information retrieval), either a single stage of handling, or the whole system-wide handling.
[src:embos/task-computing] The term task in OS/360 through z/OS is roughly equivalent to light-weight process; the tasks in a job step share an address space.
[src:embos/task-computing] However, in MVS/ESA through z/OS, a task or Service Request Block (SRB) may have access to other address spaces via its access list.
[src:embos/task-computing] The term *task* is used in the Linux kernel (at least since v2.6.13, up to and including v4.8) to refer to a unit of execution, which may share various system resources with other tasks on the system.
[src:embos/task-computing] Depending on the level of sharing, the task may be regarded as a conventional thread or process.
[src:embos/task-computing] Tasks are brought into existence using the `clone()` system call, where a user can specify the desired level of resource sharing.
[src:embos/task-computing] The term was popularized with the introduction of OS/360 (announced 1964), which featured Multiprogramming with a Fixed number of Tasks (MFT) and Multiprogramming with a Variable number of Tasks (MVT).
[src:embos/task-computing] In this case tasks were identified with light-weight processes, a job consisted of a number of tasks, and, later, tasks could have sub-tasks (in modern terminology, child processes).
[src:embos/task-computing] Today the term "task" is used very ambiguously.
[src:embos/task-computing] For example, the Windows Task Manager manages (running) *processes*, while Windows Task Scheduler schedules *programs* to execute in future, what is traditionally known as a job scheduler, and uses the `.job` extension.
[src:embos/task-computing] By contrast, the term "task queue" is commonly used in the sense of "units of work".
